column12: Exporting Australia's renewable energy via international trading swaps of ammonia.
column13: A method of exporting Australia's renewable energy via international trading swaps of ammonia, said method comprising the steps of: Building in Australia a renewable ammonia production plant which does not use fossil hydrocarbons as either a feedstock for hydrogen production or as an energy source to power the plant but rather uses renewable energy resources such as solar, wind, tidal or geothermal energy to both generate hydrogen from water and to power the other components of the plant and; Marketing the resulting renewable ammonia to distant and logistically difficult markets by harnessing international commodity trading swaps of ammonia so as to avoid the need to physically transfer the renewable ammonia to the distant markets.

column12: Rotary heat exchanger and a method of desulpherising flue gas
column13: A method of cooling a first gas (70) and heating a second gas (72, 73) wherein the first gas passes through rotatable heat transfer elements (61) at a high input temperature in a first direction, and the second gas enters the heat transfer elements at a temperature lower than that of the first gas. A first fraction (72) of the second gas passes through the heat transfer elements in a first direction, and the remaining fraction (73) of the second gas passes through the heat transfer elements in the opposite direction. To desulpherise a flue gas (71), it is passed through a sea water scrubber (figure 1, 109). The design of the heat exchanger prevents condensation forming by keeping temperatures away from the dew point of water.

column12: Using rail infrastructure for renewable ammonia production and transport
column13: The present invention relates broadly to a method of using Australia's rail infrastructure for the production and transport of renewable ammonia (NH3), said method comprising the steps of: developing in a renewable energy rich regional Australian location one or more renewable ammonia production and storage plants by using renewable energy to generate hydrogen and nitrogen and to power a synthesiser and liquefaction unit so as to produce renewable NH3 in liquid form; and transporting such liquid NH3 from the regional production and storage centre to domestic and export markets via freight trains whose rail infrastructure is located close to the NH3 production facility.

column13: Patents Act 1990 Exporting renewable hydrogen via offshore MCH platform The present invention relates generally to a method of exporting renewable hydrogen via an offshore MCH production platform, involving the following steps: 1. generating electricity onshore from a source of renewable energy; 2. transmitting this electricity to an offshore platform to power items of plant located thereon which produce Hydrogen and combine it with Toluene to produce Methylcyclohexane (MCH); 4. storing the produced MCH in holding tanks on board of the offshore platform until such time as the MCH is offloaded to transport ships which berth alongside and then transport such MCH to an export destination.

column13: A method for generating ammonia using renewable energy to power a distributed energy hub for zero carbon production of hydrogen and electricity for stationary and mobile use. The method comprising the steps of: (a) Using renewable energy to generate hydrogen and nitrogen and to power a synthesiser and liquefaction unit so as to produce renewable NH3; (b) Transporting this renewable NH3 via ship, road, rail or pipeline to a distributed energy hub; (c) Configuring equipment at this energy hub to consist of a tank to hold liquid NH3, an NH3 powered electricity generator such as an engine, gas turbine or fuel cell, a cracking unit to split H2 from NH3 and equipment to compress and dispense H2 for fuel cell vehicle use; (d) Additionally locating at or near the energy hub a fast charging electricity recharger for battery electric vehicles where the electricity is sourced from the energy hub's NH3 powered electricity generating unit, (e) Additionally locating at the energy hub connection equipment and wiring to enable the hub to supply to nearby customers or into the local electricity distribution grid electricity sourced from the energy hub's NH3 powered electricity generating unit, and (f) Efficiently configuring the energy hub's equipment such that waste heat from the electricity generating unit provides the heat requirements of the cracker unit whilst NH3 and H2 gases in the waste stream from the cracker unit are fed back as part of the fuel supply to the electricity generating unit.

column12: Powering trains and trams in Australia with locally produced renewable ammonia.
column13: Abstract The present invention relates broadly to a method of powering trains and trams in Australia with locally produced renewable ammonia. Wherein the method of powering trains and trams using renewable energy, such as solar, wind, tidal or geothermal energy to power water electrolysis for hydrogen and to power air separation units for nitrogen and to power the balance of plant to synthesise these two gases into ammonia; and storing such renewable ammonia in liquid form in on-board storage tanks located on a train; and deploying on such train modified or specially built gen-sets to generate electricity for the train's propulsion motors where instead of the gen-sets being fuelled by diesel they are fuelled by renewable ammonia from the on-board storage tanks so as to power the train's propulsion via carbon free fuel.

column12: VARIABILITY CHARACTERIZATION WITH TRUNCATED ORDERED SAMPLE SIMULATION
column13: A computing system implementing a design characterization tool can sample a distribution of values describing manufacturing variation for an integrated circuit described by a circuit design. The design characterization tool can utilize a set of the samples to generate a surrogate model of the circuit design, and can order another set of the samples based on predicted outputs of the surrogate model. The design characterization tool can simulate the surrogate model or the circuit design utilizing the ordered samples, and stop the simulations prior to all of the samples from the distribution having been utilized in the simulations. The design characterization tool can utilize a confidence interval stopping condition or a drought stopping condition to determine when to stop the simulations. The design characterization tool can utilize results of the simulations to characterize operational variation of the circuit design to the manufacturing variation described in the distribution of the values.

column12: DISTRIBUTION ESTIMATION OF MANUFACTURING VARIABILITY CHARACTERISTICS THROUGH QUANTILE SAMPLING
column13: A computing system implementing a design characterization tool can sample a distribution of values for manufacturing variation of an integrated circuit described by a circuit design. The design characterization tool can order the samples based on predicted output values of the circuit design set with characteristics in the samples of the values for manufacturing variation. The computing system can implement an analog simulator to simulate the circuit design utilizing a subset of the samples of values for manufacturing variation to identify simulated output values for an output distribution model. The design characterization tool can estimate an error in the order of the samples associated with the predicted outputs of the circuit design based on the simulated output values in the output distribution model. The design characterization tool can modify the output distribution model to correct a bias based on the estimated error in the order of the samples.

An actuator is provided. The actuator includes a rod having a socket portion at one distal end of the rod and a swivel cap. The swivel cap includes a base portion having an inner surface and an outer surface and a raised domed portion disposed on the inner surface of the base portion. The outer surface has an origin of the radius at the center of the plane that defines the outer surface of the base portion. The raised domed portion is mounted on the socket portion of the rod and has an origin of the radius on the plane that defines the outer surface of the base portion. A raised region is located on at least one of the raised domed portion or the socket portion. The swivel cap tilts relative to the rod in response to angular misalignment with a load to a tilt angle.

column12: Multicombination vehicle and method for transporting a payload in an underground mine
column13: A multicombination vehicle and method are provided for transporting a payload, such as a mined metal ore, over the roadways existing in an underground mine. The multicombination vehicle includes a powered towing unit, which may comprise a rigid body truck, and at least one towed unit mechanically coupled to the rigid body truck. The vehicle may also include a plurality of the towed units, with a forward most one of the units coupled to the rigid body truck and each adjacent pair of the towed units being coupled to one another. Each of the units includes a chassis, a plurality of wheeled axles connected to the chassis for supporting the respective unit as the vehicle travels over the roadways of the mine, and a draw frame attached to and extending rearwardly from the corresponding chassis, with a coupling attached to a rear end of the draw frame. Each towed unit may comprise a semi-trailer mounted on a dolly, with a drawbar attached to and extending forwardly from the dolly and connected with the coupling of the immediately forward unit of the vehicle. The multicombination vehicle is configured so as to minimize the swept path width of the vehicle as the vehicle negotiates turns. This is accomplished by providing each of the towed units with a dolly drawbar length having a value of less than 3.0 meters and establishing a ratio of the coupling overhang-to-wheelbase, for each of the units, of at least 0.5.

액추에이터가 제공된다. 액추에이터는 로드의 원위 단에 소켓 부분을 갖는 상기 로드와 스위블 캡을 포함한다. 스위블 캡은, 내면과 외면 및 베이스 부분의 내면에 배치되는 높인 반구형 부분을 포함한다. 외면은, 베이스 부분의 외면을 규정하는 평면의 중심에 반경의 기원을 갖는다. 높여진 반구형 부분은 로드의 소켓 부분상에 장착되고 베이스 부분의 외면을 규정하는 평면상에 반경의 기원을 갖는다. 높인 영역이 높인 반구형 부분 또는 소켓 부분 중 적어도 하나에 위치된다. 스위블 캡은 하중과의 각도 부정합에 따라 상기 로드에 관하여 경사각으로 경사진다.

column13: A heat tracing tape which can be cut to required lengths has a heating element comprising at least two lengths of woven or braided resistance wire each in the form of a flat strip. The strips are encased in extruded silicone rubber whereby they are spaced from one another. The strips are electrically connected at one end by a connector and the tape is provided with a power supply termination either at its other end, or at a T-branch connection, for connecting the tape to the power control system. The power control system is adjustable to set an estimated value of power required to maintain a predetermined process temperature. The system automatically adjusts the power supplied to the tape to the estimated value by means of a feedback control system. A process temperature sensor also regulates the power supplied to the tape in accordance with a sensed temperature.

column12: PALLET FOR SUPPORT AND TRANSPORT OF LARGE BAG-LIKE CONTAINERS
column13: A pallet is constructed in the nature of a slip-sheet for the support and transport of bulk-bags. The pallet (1) is fabricated from semi-rigid plastic sheet to have a base (2) supporting lift tine engagement elements (3) standing proud of an obverse face. Preferably two engagement elements (3) are provided. The elements (3) may be moulded from the material of the base (2) or formed by separate elements (3) attached to the base (2). At one end a flap (2a) may be provided on the base (2) to extend beyond the associated end opening (4a) of the elements (3). The extension flap (2a) may be formed by an integral part of the base or by a separate projecting tab (10) affixed to the base (2). A fold line (9) can be formed to delineate the extension (2a) from the base (2) and facilitate the upward folding thereof. A bulk-bag charged with granulated, powdered or similar material seated on the pallet (1) will settle over the elements (3) tending to locate it thereon. The pallet (1) can be moved either by inserting lifting means into the elements (3), or where provided gripping the extension (2a) and sliding.

column12: IMPROVED SAFETY QUICK LOCK FOR MOUNTING ELECTRICAL FIXTURES
column13: A lock/unlock mechanism for activating and deactivating the button of a safety quick lock device for electrical fixtures. The mechanism comprises an arm secured in the vicinity of a button for rotation, about an axis of rotation, between an active and inactive position. The cam surface is secured the arm, offset from the axis of rotation. When the arm is rotated from inactive to active position, this causes the cam surface to move the button, against a bias, fr om non-depressed to depressed position so the safety quick lock device can be engaged or disengaged. Rotation of the arm from active to inactive position causes the cam surface to allow the button to return, under the bias, to non--depressed position, whereby the connectors, if in engaged position, are locked in that position.

column13: 783,346. Valve amplifying circuits. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. Oct. 4, 1955 [Jan. 18, 1955], No. 1468/55. Class 40(6). An amplifier in which the phase-shift/frequency characteristic is a function of signal amplitude comprises a valve 5 with non-linear anode and cathode impedances A, K respectively. As shown, each impedance comprises a resistor A2, K2, respectively shunted by a rectifier A3, K3 in series with a blocking condenser A5, K5. The circuit elements are so chosen and the biases applied to the rectifiers from potentiometers A4, K4 so set that for low frequencies the distortions introduced by the networks A, K balance out and the amplifier is linear. At higher frequencies, however, an additional condenser A1 shunting the anode load destroys the balance and causes the phaseshift to vary with signal amplitude. Additional variable resistors A6, K6 may be used in order to obtain a desired characteristic. As shown, the amplifier is preceded by a cathode-follower 2 with D.C.-restoring diode 3 in its grid circuit. The arrangement is more particularly intended for use in colour picture transmission, to apply correction for non-linear phase distortion produced in the modulator.

column12: Connector half having connector wafer retained therein
column13: In a connector half, substantially parallel transverse walls joined by perpendicular sides to provide a substantially rectangular cross-section to receive at least one flat connector wafer inserted therein in a forward axial direction. A transverse rib is formed on an upper face of a wafer facing an inner face of a transverse wall. A spring clip cantilevered of the inner face of the connector half is provided. When the wafer is inserted in the connector half, the rib acts as a cam against the spring clip, forcing the spring clip up. column12: HEAT TRACING TAPE AND POWER CONTROL SYSTEM
column13: A heat tracing tape which can be cut to required lengths has a heating element comprising at least two lengths of woven or braided resistance wire each in the form of a flat strip. The strips are encased in extruded silicone rubber whereby they are spaced from one another. The strips are electrically connected at one end by a connector and the tape is provided with a power supply termination either at its other end, or at a T-branch connection, for connecting the tape to the power control system. The power control system is adjustable to set an estimated value of power required to maintain a predetermined process temperature. The system automatically adjusts the power supplied to the tape to the estimated value by means of a feedback control system. A process temperature sensor also regulates the power supplied to the tape in accordance with a sensed temperature.

column12: System and method for managing business meetings
column13: A system and method for monitoring and/or managing a business meeting, the system including a processor, memory circuitry, timer circuitry, a display and an electronic sensor. The electronic sensor scans an identification device of each attendee arriving at or withdrawing from the meeting to acquire individual unit time cost and/or individual identification data. The processor adds or subtracts individual unit time cost data to a total unit time cost parameter stored in the memory circuitry each time that an identification device is scanned by the electronic sensor, and calculates a metered cost parameter based upon the total unit time cost parameter and elapsed time data from the timer circuitry. The processor also increases or decrease a total number of attendees parameter each time an identification device is scanned. The system displays a number of time and/or cost related parameters of the meeting, such as the metered cost, the total elapsed time, and the total number of attendees. The system may be coupled to an external computer system to remotely monitor and/or to download data from the meeting.

column12: Improvements in or relating to valve amplifier circuits for phase-amplitude characteristic correction
column13: 781,887. Valve amplifying circuits. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. Sept. 28, 1955 [Jan. 18, 1955], No. 1467/55. Class 40 (6). A linear amplifier in which the phase shift is a function of signal amplitude comprises a pair of non-linear amplifiers B, C, with their outputs and inputs in parallel, one of which is preceded by a time-delay circuit E. The signal is applied to a cathode-follower Al with D.C.-restoring diode A2 in its grid circuit, which feeds amplifier B through a time-delay circuit E of variable length and attenuation, and amplifier C through a variable attenuator C8. Each amplifier comprises two stages B1, B2 and C1, C2, respectively, in cascade and each stage is provided with a cathode feedback resistor, e.g. B4, shunted with a rectifier, e.g. B5, in series with a blocking condenser, e.g. B7. Each rectifier is supplied with an adjustable bias from a potentiometer, e.g. B6, the rectifiers being oppositely poled in the two stages of each amplifier and also in the corresponding stages of the two amplifiers. A D.C. restoring diode is provided in the grid circuit of each of the stages B2, C2. The outputs are combined in a common anode resistor D1 and are fed to the output via a cathode follower D2. The arrangement is so adjusted that with zero time-delay in the circuit E the overall input/output characteristic is linear. In a modification, the amplifiers are arranged in cascade, the timedelay circuit then being connected in parallel with one of them (Fig. 2, not shown). The arrangement is more particularly intended for use in colour picture transmission, to apply correction for non-linear phase distortion produced in the modulator.

An actuator is provided. The actuator includes: a housing having an interior elongated hole; a rod dimensioned to fit in the elongated hole; a piston dimensioned to fit in and move along the elongated hole while connected to the rod; mating structure located on at least one of the piston and rod, the mating structure configured to allow the rod to attach to the piston in a manner to create clearance between the rod and the piston to allow the rod and piston to move with respect to each other. A method of attaching a piston to a rod in an actuator may also be provided. The method may include: fitting the piston to the rod; providing a clearance between the piston and the rod; fastening the piston to the rod in a loose manner as to preserve the clearance and allow the piston to move with respect to the rod.

column12: MULTI-COMBINATION VEHICLE INCORPORATING AN ELECTRONICALLY COUPLED POWER TRAILER
column13: The present invention is for a multi-combination vehicle including a prime mover having an engine and at least one powered trailer mechanically coupled to the prime mover. A control system measures the relative motion or force between the two, preferably by the use of a load cell and accordingly adjusts the operation of the engine on the power trailer so that the powered trailer and the prime mover are synchronized in their movement. This allows a multi-combination vehicle to carry a significant load, by providing sufficient motive power without the potential for damage to the transmission and differential system of the prime mover.

column13: 745,947. Valve modulating and amplifying circuits. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. June 21, 1954 [Aug. 12, 1953], No. 22276/53. Classes 40 (5) and 40 (6). Wide-band modulating potentials are superimposed in the grid circuit of a driven wide-band amplifier stage to which a narrow-band driving carrier-frequency amplifier is coupled through a constant impedance network comprising at least two sections. In one embodiment the driving amplifier V1 has an anode circuit L1, C1, sharply tuned to the carrier frequency input and coupled to inductance 2L1. (The numerical part of the references is not a multiplier but merely a distinguishing number.) The first network section comprises the elements L, C, R dimensioned so that #L/C=R. Inductance 2L1 is of such a value that it tunes capacitance C to the carrier frequency. Capacitance 2C1 is included to tune the inductance L to the carrier frequency. A second network section comprises elements 2L, 2C, 2R dimensioned as in the first section and capacitance 3C1 and inductance 3L1 are included to tune inductance 2L and capacitance 2C, respectively, to the carrier frequency. The wide-band modulating source M is included in the shunt arm 2C, 2R, across the input grid circuit of the wide-band driven amplifier V2. The second network section includes an effective resistance R which is presented by the whole network consisting of the elements L1, C1, 2L1, C, L, 2C1, and R connected between earth and the junction of 2C1 and 2L, and which is numerically equal, over the narrow band of the driving stage, to the value of the resistance 2R. A further similar embodiment is described in which the elements of the network are arranged differently and the input capacitance of stage V2 is tuned to the carrier frequency, Fig. 2 (not shown).

column12: AV Timing Measurement and Correction for Digital Television
column13: An invention for measuring, maintaining and correcting synchronization between signals which suffer varying relative delays during transmission and/or storage is shown. The present invention teaches measuring the relative delay between a plurality of signals which have suffered differing delays due to transmission, storage or other processing. The preferred embodiment of the invention includes the use of a marker which is generated in response to a second signal and combined with a first signal in a manner which ensures that the marker will not be lost in the expected processing of the first signal. Subsequently a first delayed marker is generated in response to the marker associated with or recovered from the first signal, and a second delayed marker is generated from the second signal. The first delayed marker and second delayed marker are compared to determine a measure of the relative timing or delay between said first signal and said second signal at said subsequent time.

The preferred embodiment of the invention includes the use of a marker which is generated in response to a second signal and combined with a first signal in a manner which ensures that the marker will not be lost in the expected processing of the first signal. Subsequently a first delayed marker is generated in response to the marker associated with or recovered from the first signal, and a second delayed marker is generated from the second signal. The first delayed marker and second delayed marker are compared to determine a measure of the relative timing or delay between said first signal and said second signal at said subsequent time.

column12: System and Method for AV Sync Correction by Remote Sensing
column13: Method and system for measuring audio video synchronization. This is done by having a remote sensing station to measure and process the audio and images from a multimedia terminal that displays a television program. The remote sensing station uses an audio sensor to sense the audio signal from the multimedia station and an image sensor to sense the images displayed on the multimedia station. An AV processing circuit in the remote sensing terminal processes the signals from the audio sensor and the sensed images. The delay information is then communicated to the multimedia station to adjust the AV synchronization.

[Also in Group XL (c)] In a balanced modulator for television signals the modulator output during line synchronizing pulses is passed through an electronic switch and the rectified out-. put of the switch applied as negative feedback to the input of one at least of the modulating valves so that the balanced modulated output at these instants is made zero. As shown, synchronizing pulses P and colour signals from a source 1 are applied through a phase splitter 2 in opposite phases to grids 3a of modulating valves 3 and subcarrier frequency from a source 8 applied through an amplifier 9 in opposite phases to suppressor grids 3b of the valves 3. The combined outputs of the valves 3, after suppression of any harmonics by a circuit 14 are applied to an output terminal 15 and to a switch valve 21 rendered conductive only during synchronizing pulses by pulses applied to its cathode from the source 1 through valves 18, 19. The sub-carrier frequency output of the switch 21 and also sub-carrier from the amplifiers 9, 22 may then be both applied to a rectifier 23-26 whose D.C. output variable corresponding to the sense of any unbalance of the modulating valves 3 is applied in series with the bias from source 20 to one of the modulating valves 3. The source 1 also passes its output to a synchronizing pulse separator valve 4a, whose anode circuit includes a delay line 4b with short-circuited remote end so that partly overlapping negative-going pulses and reflected positive-going pulses produce an output P<SP>1</SP> of alternately negative and positive-going narrow pulses, of which the negative-going are removed by a valve 4d, and positive and negative-going pulses derived from a phase splitter 4e and used as clamping pulses to connect the grids 3a of the modulating valves 3 to bias sources HT+ and 29 through D.C. restoring diode bridges 5a, 5b at back porch intervals succeeding the synchronizing pulses. The transformer winding 10a and amplifier 22a may be omitted so that the system only operates to correct errors in one sense. Also a reversing switch may be connected to the rectifier output so that the correction can be applied to either modulating valve

column12: A DRIVE TRAIN ASSEMBLY FOR USE IN POWERED VEHICLES OR TRAILERS
column13: A drive train assembly for use in powered vehicles or trailers having at least one axle of driving wheels. The assembly includes a coupling mechanism coupling the engine of the vehicle and the driving wheels. The coupling mechanism is activatable between a first and a second state, wherein in the first state the engine and driving wheels are mechanically uncoupled and in the second state the engine is mechanically coupled to the driving wheels. When the driving wheels are rotated by the vehicle or trailer being towed and the engine turned off the coupling mechanism ensures that no parts of the drive train assembly do not rotate and are therefore damaged due to lack of lubrication. Two embodiments are disclosed, one with the coupling (138) in the transfer box (110), and in the second embodiment the coupling is in the wheel hub assembly. Also disclosed is an oil pump assembly driven by the wheels rather than the drive train to provide some lubrication when the wheels are rotating and the engine is off.

Class 40 (6) Frequency-conscious feedback is used to extend the response of an amplifier to frequencies at which it would otherwise be falling. As applied to an amplifier, Fig. 2, comprising a first stage 1 resistance-capacity coupled to a cathode-follower 7, loss of gain at the higher frequencies caused by stray capacitance Cl in shunt to the load resistance R1 is compensated by feedback introduced by a capacitor C2 interconnecting the cathode circuits. As shown, negative feedback is applied to the stage 1 by means of a resistance RF between anode and grid of the valve. Another embodiment, Fig. 3, comprises a four stage amplifier in which negative feedback is applied over the first three stages V1-3 by means of a resistance RF interconnecting the cathode circuits of the first and third valves ; a capacitor CF in shunt with the resistance RF extends the highfrequency response. The overall response is extended by means of a capacitor Cx between the cathodes of the first and final stages.

column12: System and method for managing business meetings
column13: A system and method for monitoring and/or managing a business meeting, the system including a processor, memory circuitry, timer circuitry, a display and an electronic sensor. The electronic sensor scans an identification device of each attendee arriving at or withdrawing from the meeting to acquire individual unit time cost and/or individual identification data. The processor adds or subtracts individual unit time cost data to a total unit time cost parameter stored in the memory circuitry each time that an identification device is scanned by the electronic sensor, and calculates a metered cost parameter based upon the total unit time cost parameter and elapsed time data from the timer circuitry. The processor also increases or decrease a total number of attendees parameter each time an identification device is scanned. The system displays a number of time and/or cost related parameters of the meeting, such as the metered cost, the total elapsed time, and the total number of attendees. The system may be coupled to an external computer system to remotely monitor and/or to download data from the meeting.

column13: The present invention is directed to an apparatus and method for defining a landscape boundary. The invention comprises a longitudinal log having spaced apart ends, one of which is pronged and the other is flanged. The pronged and flanged ends are configured so as to engage one another by virtue of a pivot pin or locking pin arrangement. In this fashion, several logs can be fastened together and arranged in a variety of curved paths if necessary so as to define a landscape boundary. The invention also includes a lighting element to provide illumination to the landscape where the invention is used. The method of the present invention is directed to the steps of constructing a landscape boundary incorporating the apparatus of the present invention.

column12: Improvements in or relating to television and like transmitter installations
column13: 701,482. Television. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. Oct. 17, 1952 [Feb. 11, 1952], No. 3614/52. Class 40 (3). [Also in Group XXXV] In a television or like installation of the kind in which a single carrier source is connected to the aerial or load through two or more channels, each giving an ouput of constant amplitude, phase relation at the common output is corrected and maintained by comparing the combined output with a standard output (a little below that which obtains when the outputs are exactly in phase), and using the resulting voltage to control the phase shift in one or more channels. As shown, the carrier source C.D. feeds two driver stages A1, A2, one in each channel, which feed modulating amplifiers B1, B2 whose output is combined in a mixer PM and fed to a load. The mixer output is also taken to a control circuit F for producing a D.C. potential responsive to departure from a predetermined level which may be fixed at 98 per cent of the level which would be obtained if the two channels were operating in phase agreement. The D.C. potential is thus applied in the corrective sense to the grid of a phase-control valve 1 associated with a condenser 4 in a tuned circuit 5 of the driver stage A2. Each of the amplifiers B1, B2, is provided with an automatic amplitude control circuit of the kind described in Specification 668,728, their output being rectified m gated rectifiers El, E2 and the resultants fed to control circuits D1, D2 which control the modulators C1, C2 so as to maintain constant the black levels in the outputs of each channel. Gating of the rectifiers El, E2 renders them effective only at the instants of transition from picture signal to sync. signal and vice-versa; and similar gating is provided for the control circuit F. The phase control system is applicable to television transmitters using either positive or negative picture signal modulation. In the latter case, the D.C. control potential may be derived from the combined output at PM by a peak voltmeter responsive to the positive-going sync. signals, and gating is not required.

column12: Improvements in or relating to grid modulated radio transmitters
column13: 736,492. Automatic voltage control systems. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. Feb. 11, 1952 [June 27, 1951], No. 15278/51. Addition to 695,416. Class 38 (4). [Also in Group XL (c)] The drive applied to a variable impedance load from a radio frequency source is maintained constant by rectification to produce a control voltage which is utilized to vary the drive in such a manner as to oppose change in output level. In a transmitter comprising a grid modulated stage 13 driven with R.F. via cascaded stages 3, 7, the stage 7 being a cathode-follower and 5, 10, 14 representing tuned circuits, the voltage across the tuned circuit 10 is rectified by a rectifier 15. The rectified voltage, after optional amplification in an amplifier 16 is applied to the grid of a control valve 18 which, together with a resistance 6 forms a potentiometer supplying H.T. to the amplifier 3. In this way the gain of the stage 3 is varied in such a manner as to maintain the R.F. potential across the circuit 10 constant. Control may alternatively be applied to the grid or cathode of the valve 3, or if this comprises a screen-grid valve, to the screen.

column12: Control structure in a document processing system.
column13: A document processing system including a novel control structure having separated supervisory and document functions. The document functions, including a document buffer (54) and document access control means (60), are the sole means for accessing documents. The document function routines (42) are selected from a predetermined library of such routines. The system includes a flexible, expandable document structure (32) incorporating information item blocks (86) and indexing blocks related through pointers. A new structure of the bus for conducting the documents and the routines between system memory and workstations is disclosed.

column12: HEAT TRACING TAPE AND POWER CONTROL SYSTEM
column13: A heat tracing tape which can be cut to required lengths has a heating element comprising at least two lengths of woven or braided resistance wire each in the form of a flat strip. The strips are encased in extruded silicone rubber whereby they are spaced from one another. The strips are electrically connected at one end by a connector and the tape is provided with a power supply termination either at its other end, or at a T-branch connection, for connecting the tape to the power control system. The power control system is adjustable to set an estimated value of power required to maintain a predetermined process temperature. The system automatically adjusts the power supplied to the tape to the estimated value by means of a feedback control system. A process temperature sensor also regulates the power supplied to the tape in accordance with a sensed temperature.

column12: Improvements in or relating to radio navigation aids
column13: 1,024,982. Radio navigational aids. MARCONI CO. Ltd. Jan. 2, 1964 [Feb. 21, 1963], No. 6955/63. Heading H4D. A radio navigation aid for a moving vehicle S1, Fig. 1, comprises an area surveillance pulse radar A, producing a normal P.P.I. display including a clockwise rotating strobe indicating the direction of the radar beam, which display is viewed by a television camera and transmitted, in the form of television signals, from a transmitter T for reception and display by a television receiver, Fig. 3 (not shown), on board the vehicle S1, the vehicle also being provided with means, responsive to the passage through the vehicle of the radar beam and independent of the display, for indicating when the rotating strobe passes through the response of the vehicle. The indicating means may be a gas discharge tube R6, mounted on an annular track R7 so as to be movable around the display tube to follow the rotating strobe AB, and energized from means responsive to the radar pulses from the transmitter T. Where additional means of identifying the vehicle S1 are needed, a second transmitting point B may be provided, producing a rotating beam BB in synchronism with beam AB, and energized, either by transmitter A or by its own transmitter. A rotating strobe representing beam BB may be provided on the display at A and transmitted for display on the vehicle in the same manner as the rest of the display, or signals representing the said rotating strobe may be electronically added to the energy transmitted from T. A second indicator R6<SP>1</SP> may be provided for indicating when the beam BB passes through the vehicle, and may be energized by means R5, in parallel with the first indicating means R6, when the frequencies of the two beams are the same, or, by separate frequency selective means R5<SP>1</SP> when the two frequencies are different. The transmitting point B may alternatively radiate a clockwise rotating overlapping-lobe equisignal beam, with the means energizing indicator R6<SP>1</SP> being responsive to an equality of received signal and the indicator R6<SP>1</SP> being a zero centre scale pointer indicating instrument, or a lamp indicating the passage of the equi-signal line through the vehicle. The invention may be used for airport traffic control.

column13: 668,728. Television. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. June 2, 1949 [Aug. 10, 1948], No. 21105/48. Class 40 (iii). [Also in Group XXXV] The " black " level in a television transmission system is maintained at a predetermined value by means of a control voltage derived from the modulated output of the system and utilized to control the modulation. The invention is applicable to a system of the kind in which the vision and synchronizing signals are transmitted as carrier variations on opposite sides of a predetermined level (i.e. the " black " level) and is described as applied to a transmitter such as that shown in Fig. 1 in which a radio-frequency carrier wave source A is fed to a grid modulated amplifier B to which is also fed the modulation signal from the modulator C. In accordance with the present invention the modulated output from B is rectified at E and fed to a circuit D from which a correcting control voltage is supplied to the modulation source C when the "black" level of the output from B departs from a predetermined value. Fig. 2 shows details of the circuit of D, Fig. 1, and comprises a first stage 3 which separates the synchronizing signals from the vision signals, the former signals then being differentiated in a stage 4 and limited in a further stage 5 to provide narrow pulses for the control of a Schmitt type relay comprising valves 6 and 7 which supplies short duration " opening pulses to a gating valve 8 to allow a " sample of the rectified modulated output (fed to valve 8 over conductor 9) to be passed to an amplifier 10. Succeeding amplifier 10 is a circuit including valves 11, 12 and 14 which provides the required controlling potential. This potential, which is developed across the cathode resistance of valve 14, is then fed to the modulation signal source, e.g. C, Fig. 1, to control its amplitude to compensate for variations in the D.C. level of the transmitted signal.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the Control of Dynamo Electric Machinery.
column13: 129,828. Wilson, J. C. July 29, 1918. Exciting.-To minimize the lag or delay in regulation due to the self-induction of the fieldmagnet circuit of dynamo-electric machines, an additional winding a<x>, Fig. 1, is arranged on the field-magnet system of the main machine a and is connected in circuit with an additional winding d<2> on the exciter d, the windings a<x>, d<2> being connected also to a constant-potential source l. When the current flowing through the main field winding a<1> of the machine a is being increased by a manipulation of a regulating-resistance b in the circuit of the exciter main field winding d<1>, an electromotive force is induced in the current containing the coils a<x>, d<2> by transformer action of the winding a<1> on the winding a<x>, and the consequent alteration of the current through the winding d<2> has the effect of causing the exciter d to increase its voltage, producing an increased current in the winding a<1>. Similarly, decrease of current in the winding a<1> causes an automatic further decrease of voltage in the exciter d. In a modification, Fig. 2, the main machine a has one field-magnet winding a<x> connected to a source of exciting-current in series with an auxiliary machine f which may oppose or assist the voltage of the source l by suitable adjustment of the field regulator b ; additional windings a<1>, f<2> on the main and auxiliary machines are also connected together and to the source l. The invention is applicable to dynamo-electric machines employed in the driving of rolling-mills.

A system for quickly mounting and grounding electrical fixtures with respect to flush mounted electrical junction boxes is provided. The system comprises an electrically conductive mount bracket for releasably securing on and across the junction box mounted flushly on a support surface. A ground wire to be secured to the electrical fixture is secured to the mount bracket so as to support the weight of the electrical fixture when suspended from the mount bracket by the ground wire. An anchor post is centrally secured to the mount bracket so as to extend outwardly away from the junction box when the mounted bracket is in a secured position on the junction box. An extension post is provided together with an attachment to releasably secure the extension post to the anchor post so that the electrical fixture is releasably supported in operative position on the extension post.

column12: AV timing measurement and correction for digital television
column13: An invention for measuring, maintaining and correcting synchronization between signals which suffer varying relative delays during transmission and/or storage is shown. The present invention teaches measuring the relative delay between a plurality of signals which have suffered differing delays due to transmission, storage or other processing. The preferred embodiment of the invention includes the use of a marker which is generated in response to a second signal and combined with a first signal in a manner which ensures that the marker will not be lost in the expected processing of the first signal. Subsequently a first delayed marker is generated in response to the marker associated with or recovered from the first signal, and a second delayed marker is generated from the second signal. The first delayed marker and second delayed marker are compared to determine a measure of the relative timing or delay between said first signal and said second signal at said subsequent time.

ELECTROMAGNETICALLY OPERATED VALVE ASSEMBLY AND MANUFACTURE OF IT
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To easily change the position of an electric terminal in relation to a main body, in an electromagnetically operated valve. SOLUTION: A solenoid actuator 12 in which a solenoid coil 64 is shut up in a container is provided. This solenoid actuator 12 is provided with a plurality of teeth on the end outer front surface of the container. When the solenoid actuator 12 is combined with a valve main body 14, the teeth of the container are engaged with a plurality of teeth formed on guide members 50, 54. The direction of the solenoid actuator 12 in relation to the guide members 50, 54 can be changed by changing the engaging positions of these teeth. Since an electric terminal is integrated with the solenoid actuator 12, the position of the electric terminal in relation to the valve main body 14 can be also changed.

Improvements relating to colour television apparatus
column13: 782,461. Colour television. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. Jan. 30, 1956 [April 29, 1955], No. 12424/55. Class 40 (3). In colour television apparatus employing a signal of the colour subcarrier type and in which a subcarrier synchronizing " burst " occurs during the back porch following the line synchronizing pulse, a D.C. restorer circuit comprises a conventional diode restorer 2 connected to the grid of an amplifier 3, through which the video signals pass, together with a four-diode gate 10 which is arranged to sample the output of the amplifier for a period during the back porch and apply back a correcting potential to the amplifier grid. The input to gate 10 is derived via cathode follower 6 and the correcting potential output is applied via a further cathode follower 11. During the periods between sampling, the correcting potential persists since the leakage of voltage from the capacitance at grid of cathode follower 11 is negligible when the gate 10 is open. Pulses to control gate 10 are derived by separating positive-going sync. pulses from a video signal input at 31 in separator stage 32 and applying them to a short-circuited delay line 35. The combination of original and reflected pulses at a tap 36 results in a pair of oppositely-poled pulses of reduced duration (3 micro-seconds) for each sync. pulse. The second pulse of each pair, which is of positive polarity and may be arranged to occur a short while, for example, half a microsecond, after the sync. pulse termination, is selected by a valve 37 and applied to a phase splitter stage 38 to derive positive and negative pulses to control gate 10. If desired, A.C. coupling may be provided between amplifier 3 and cathode follower 6 provided the time-constant of the coupling is large compared with any unwanted variation it is desired to correct. In a modification, Fig. 2 (not shown), the coupling between the amplifier and cathode follower comprises a series combination of gas discharge tubes and a valve, the signal to the cathode follower being taken from across the valve. The gas discharge tubes present a high D.C. resistance and low A.C. resistance whereas the valve presents a low D.C. resistance and high A.C. resistance. Consequently only a small part of the D.C. voltage due to the coupling is applied to the cathode follower but a very large proportion of any A.C. voltage including variations it is desired to correct. A stage of D.C. amplification may be included in the feed-back loop.

column13: A synthetic peptide is provided having the amino acid sequence: KCNTATCATQRLANFLVHSSNNFGAILSSTNVGSNTY said peptide being carboxy terminally amidated and having a disulphide bond between the cysteine residues at positions 2 and 7. This is useful in treatment of diabetes mellitus. There is also provided a synthetic carboxy terminally amidated peptide which is a conservative variant of the above peptide. The peptide biological activity can be enhanced by refolding the peptide in a denaturing solution. If the peptide is produced in the form of pharmaceutical compositions, it can be obtained from the islet amyloid of diabetic pancreata by solubilising and successively subjecting to normal phase high performance liquid chromatography gel filtration and reverse phase high performance liquid chromatography followed by elution.

column12: Software and methods to detect and correct data structure
column13: Methods to detect and correct bit errors in data include the steps of specifying to a compiler a storage area with a variable wherein the variable includes a data value corresponding to its data size and an error checking code, calculating an error checking code value indicative of the corresponding data structure value, storing the variable with the error checking code value, retrieving the variable upon demand, detecting an error on the data value using the error checking code value, and correcting the error upon detection of an error on the data value. Further steps may include storing and retrieving the data structure directly onto the storage area without additional encoding and decoding circuitry, encoding and decoding the data structure without altering the data structure format during storing and retrieving from the storage area, or detecting and correcting double bit errors. Software for the methods is provided on or in a computer readable medium.

column13: A demountable system for the display of merchandise such as books, magazines, newspapers and the like. This system employs a top cap and contoured upright struts having an appropriate contour to orient shelving at different angles to the vertical from a upper most position on the strut to a lower most position. The system is easily installed or disassemblied at a particular place of business. The principal feature involves providing an open channel in the rear surface of each strut to releasably accept the edge of a spacer panel contoured to the desired configuration of the strut. In this way, the strut is always maintained in the proper configuration without the mechanical attachments of spacers and the like as previously employed. One end of each of the struts is received within a top cap and a further end engages the floor to maintain each strut in proper orientation without physical fasteners. Each strut is provided with edge recesses or grooves to accept back panels to complete the attractive feature of the shelving units. Also, each strut releasably receives an apertured face plate for the attachment of shelving units. The resultant structure is quickly and easily assemblied or disassemblied with a substantial savings in time.

A drive assembly, particularly for driving arms around a compartment in a waste material digester, comprises a rotatable hub having an inner drive plate and a ratchet plate secured thereto for rotation therewith. Positionally opposed, parallel piston and cylinder drive means recipocatably drive an outer drive plate, drive arms pivotally carried on the outer drive plate engaging with drive pins on the inner drive plate to drive the hub in one direction. Movement of the hub in the opposite direction is prevented by latches engaging with respective shoulders of the ratchet plate when the outer drive plate moves in said opposite direction.

column13: A semiconductor device includes a substrate, a drift region, a source region, a gate region, a drain contact and a base region. The substrate is doped with a first dopant type. The drift region is disposed above the substrate, and is doped with the first dopant type. The source region, doped with the first dopant type. The gate region is disposed above the drift region and above the source region. The base region is disposed between the source region and the drift region. At least a portion of the base region includes at least one trench having a vertical wall and a horizontal wall. The base region is further configured to conduct current in a horizontal direction on the vertical wall and in a horizontal direction the horizontal wall.

A rotatable building structure that comprises: a vertically extending building having one or more floors; a fixed core support for supporting the building, located substantially centrally beneath the building; a rotatable annular drive system for rotating the building, located lower than the building and with its centre substantially aligned with the vertical centreline of the building, the system having an upper surface and a planar lower surface; and a fixed outer support, located beneath the annular drive system, the support having a planar upper surface that contacts the planar lower surface of the annular drive system; wherein at least one of the lower surface of the annular drive system and the upper surface of the fixed outer support is a bearing material, permitting rotation of the annular drive system over the fixed outer support, such that the annular drive system is rotated via a planar to planar bearing system.

A heat tracing tape which can be cut to required lengths has a heating element comprising at least two lengths of woven or braided resistance wire each in the form of a flat strip. The strips are encased in extruded silicone rubber whereby they are spaced from one another. The strips are electrically connected at one end by a connector and the tape is provided with a power supply termination either at its other end, or at a T-branch connection, for connecting the tape to the power control system. The power control system is adjustable to set an estimated value of power required to maintain a predetermined process temperature. The system automatically adjusts the power supplied to the tape to the estimated value by means of a feedback control system. A process temperature sensor also regulates the power supplied to the tape in accordance with a sensed temperature.

column12: Spheroidal graphite cast iron alloy containing carbon, silicon and molybdenum and disc brake rotor thereof
column13: A spheroidal graphite cast iron alloy consisting essentially of, by weight 1.5 to 4.5% carbon, 1.5 to 4.5% silicon, 1.2 to 6.5% molybdenum, optionally nickel and/or copper, where the (% molybdenum + % nickel + % copper) does not exceed 6.5%, balance iron and incidental impurities. The alloy has a microstructure which comprises very soft nodules of graphite surrounded by relatively soft and ductile ferrite, the soft nodules of graphite being strengthened and hardened by a pearlite phase of the alloy and/or strengthened and hardened by a very hard complex carbide phase. Also described is a spheroidal graphite cast iron alloy that consists essentially of, by weight 3 to 3.35% carbon, 1.9 to 2.58% silicon and 3.0% molybdenum, balance iron and incidental impurities. Also described is a disc brake rotor manufactured wholly or partly from either of the alloys described above.

column13: A semiconductor device fabrication method includes forming first and second spaced apart base regions and source regions in a substrate with a portion of a drift region therebetween. The method further includes forming at least a first trench extending laterally through the base region, the drift region and the source region, the first trench extending vertically partially through the source region. column12: Method of making a watermarked polymeric sheet
column13: A method of making a watermarked polymeric sheet includes forming a web (22) of a polymeric material, selectively irradiating portions of the web (22) with electromagnetic radiation, and stretching the web to form a sheet (26) having increased length and/or width. The watermarked polymeric sheet (26) has a plurality of indentations in at least one surface thereof, in areas corresponding to the irradiated portions of the web. The indentations form a watermark comprising areas of increased translucency, which is visible by transmitted light. The web may be synthetic paper. It may be irradiated using a laser. The watermarked polymeric sheet may be used for banknotes, cheques, share certificates, identity cards and labels for high value products such as wine, perfume and pharmaceuticals.

column12: Improvements in Means for Fastening Doors and Windows Combined with Alarm Devices therefor
column13: 17,874. Cooper, J. C. Sept. 6. Alarms, burglar and like.-Relates to door and window fastenings, and alarm devices therefor. Fig. 1 shows a door latch or lock. The bolt d, which may be single or double locking, is mounted in guides within a casing a attached to the door post, and is kept in position by a spring o. The bolt is pressed outwards by means of springs e. A plate f attached to a bolt is adapted to make contact with plates g so as to close an electric circuit. When the bolt is retracted, the circuit is broken and an alarm bell is sounded. The mechanism may be so arranged that, normally, the circuit is broken, and upon closing the circuit, by retracting the bolt, the alarm is sounded. The circuit may be connected to a telephone, so as to ring up the exchange when the bolt is operated. An electric wave, or mechanical means, may be employed to sound the alarm. The bolt d is retracted by means of a roller j, or by an inclined or curved block, mounted on the end of a pushrod i and adapted to engage an inclined or curved piece k on the bolt. The push-rod may be connected by a system of levers to a pedal-plate, so that it may be operated by the foot. A pair of rods, extending through the casing, may be arranged to operate the bolt by a pull from one side or a push from the other side. In a double-locking arrangement, a telescopic spring cushion n is mounted on the end of a lifting-rod n<1>, and is adapted to fall between the plate f and the end of the bolt, when the latter is shot, so that the circuit is broken or completed when the bolt is retracted. When applied to a railway-carriage door, the alarm serves to call the attention of the guard to any attempt made to open a door. Fig. 5 shows a sash fastening. A bolt p. enclosed in a casing p<2> attached to one of the sashes, is forced by a spring p<1> into engagement with a hole in a socket q attached to the other sash. The end of the hole and the tip of the bolt are screwed, or the hole may be provided with a slot or slots to engage a projection or projections on the bolt, and the wires h of an electric circuit containing an alarm are connected to the socket. By screwing in the bolt so as to secure the sashes, the circuit is completed. Should the bolt be withdrawn, the circuit is broken and an alarm is sounded. The socket may be provided with a number of holes, each fitted with circuit wires, so that the window may be secured in an open position to permit of ventilation. In the arrangement shown in Fig. 8, a number of recesses t, t<1> are provided in the side frame of one or both sashes, and are adapted to engage a spring catch t<2> mounted in the window frame. Upon moving the sash, the catch is forced back and breaks or closes an electric circuit so as to sound an alarm.

column13: Dispositif de commande du curseur sensible à une pression latérale (10) permettant de déplacer des éléments mobiles affichés sur un écran d'ordinateur (14). Dans l'un des modes de réalisation, ledit dispositif de commande du curseur sensible à une pression latérale (10) fait défiler le contenu d'une fenêtre selon la position du curseur par rapport à la fenêtre. Lorsque le curseur (15) se trouve dans la fenêtre (23), une simple pression latérale sur les deux côtés opposées (30, 31) dudit dispositif de commande permet un défilement sur une courte distance. Lorsque le curseur (15) se trouve hors de la fenêtre (23), la pression latérale dudit dispositif de commande (10) permet d'obtenir un défilement sur une distance moyenne ou longue dont la sélection et la spécification sont facilitées par des indicateurs graphiques, tels que des indications de direction (63) et des ''barres d'ascenseur'' (57, 59). Un indicateur graphique du chemin produit par l'utilisateur donne la direction et la quantité de défilement sur une courte distance.

column13: SQUEEZABLE CONTROL DEVICE FOR COMPUTER DISPLAY MEANS A squeezable cursor control device provides movement of moveable entities displayed on a computerized display. In one application the squeezable cursor control device provides scrolling of window contents as a function of cursor position relative to the window. The cursor positioned within the window provides short range scrolling upon squeezing of two opposed portions of the control device. The cursor positioned outside the window provides medium and long range scrolling upon squeezing of the control device. Graphical indicators such as directional indications and elevator bars aid selection and specification of medium and long range scrolling. A graphical indicator of a user generated path provides direction and amount of scrolling in short range scrolling.

A fruit clipper with a scissor-like cutter at the front end. A spring is attached to the scissor-like cutter biasing the blades in the open position and a wire from the scissor-like cutter extends to a solenoid. When the solenoid is enabled, and the core of the solenoid is pulled into the coil it pulls the wire which in turn closes the cutter blades against the spring bias. Electrical contacts are on one of the blades and frame which are connected by a circuit to the solenoid so that when the contacts are joined the circuit is closed enabling the solenoid and closing the cutter blades. A scoop and chute assembly are disposed under the cutter blades and cut fruit drops into the scoop and is carried by gravity down the chute.

The alloy is preferably spheroidal graphite cast iron. The alloy is especially useful in manufacturing brake disc rotors.

column13: 678,060. Valve amplifying circuits. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. March 13, 1951 [July 7, 1950], No. 17094/50. Class 40 (vi). In a phase-splitter in which the output is taken from between the anode and cathode of a valve 7 having anode and cathode impedances Z3, Z4, the grid of the valve is fed from the anode of a preceding valve 1 and a feed-back path is provided between the anode of the phasesplitter and the cathode of the preceding valve. column13: One or more spinning flywheels are adapted to despin or partially despin a rotating mass such as a satellite and to convert the rotational energy into heat or electrical energy. The flywheels have one degree of freedom, parallel to the satellite, spin axis. This one degree of freedom allows the flywheel to precess in the manner of a gyroscope. As the flywheel precesses it turns a shaft which drives an electrical generator which produces electrical power that can be taken out of the despin device to drive external electrical devices that will disperse the rotational energy in the form of heat, light or electrically driven chemical changes. The flywheels exchange rotational energy after the spin vector of the spinning flywheel becomes congruent with the spin vector of the spinning satellite, thereby allowing the energy extraction process to be repeated. Bearing loss makeup energy is restored to the spinning flywheel system by feedback from the extracted satellite rotational energy.

System and method for identifying useless documents
column13: A system and method are disclosed for identifying useless or insignificant documents in a document hit list assembled from documents stored in one or more document collection databases. A search engine is used to compose the document hit list based on a query presented by a user. A text extraction algorithm run by a processor is then used to process the documents identified by the document hit list to produce a table of terms and their corresponding collection-level importance ranking called the IQ or Information Quotient. The text algorithm also produces a table of the most important terms per document. The documents are also scanned independently and a table of documents with filenames and lengths is also produced. A summarizing text algorithm is also run by a processor against the documents of the document hit list to produce a table of terms having a high tf*idf value for each document. All of the tables are stored in a relational database, which allows the system of the present invention to generate a table of terms per document ranked by decreasing IQ. To determine whether a document is useful or useless, the table of terms and IQs, the table of most important terms per document, the table of documents with filename and lengths, and the table of high tf*idf values are examined.

column12: Process for the selective production of ketones
column13: The present invention provides a process for the selective production of ketones under hydroformylation conditions. In particular, the process comprises the hydroformylation of at least one olefin in the presence of hydrogen, carbon monoxide, and a catalyst which consists essentially of triruthenium dodecacarbonyl. The olefin preferably comprises propylene. The reaction is conducted under conditions such that the ratio of olefin:ruthenium is about 200:1 to 3000:1, the ratio of carbon monoxide:hydrogen:olefin to about 1:1.4:4 to 1:6:100, the total pressure is about 500 to 10,000 psig, the carbon monoxide partial pressure is about 50 to 500 psig, and the reaction temperature is about 60.degree. to 250.degree. C.

column12: AV Timing Measurement and Correction for Digital Television
column13: An invention for measuring, maintaining and correcting synchronization between signals which suffer varying relative delays during transmission and/or storage is shown. The present invention teaches measuring the relative delay between a plurality of signals which have suffered differing delays due to transmission, storage or other processing. The preferred embodiment of the invention includes the use of a marker which is generated in response to a second signal and combined with a first signal in a manner which ensures that the marker will not be lost in the expected processing of the first signal. Subsequently a first delayed marker is generated in response to the marker associated with or recovered from the first signal, and a second delayed marker is generated from the second signal. The first delayed marker and second delayed marker are compared to determine a measure of the relative timing or delay between said first signal and said second signal at said subsequent time.

column13: HYDROFORMYLATION PROCESS WITH RHODIUM CATALYST AND OXYGEN STABILIZATION THEREOF This invention concerns an oxo process employing unmodified rhodium catalyst for the preparation of aldehydes, principally for the preparation of relatively high prop- ortions of branched isomer, from olefins and synthesis gas. column13: A method and apparatus for controlling the load presented to one or more power sources such as a power grid, backup power generator or solar panel is described. column12: Heat tracing tape and power control system.
column13: A heat tracing tape which can be cut to required lengths has a heating element comprising at least two lengths of woven or braided resistance wire each in the form of a flat strip. The strips are encased in extruded silicone rubber whereby they are spaced from one another. The strips are electrically connected at one end by a connector and the tape is provided with a power supply termination either at its other end, or at a T-branch connection, for connecting the tape to the power control system. The power control system is adjustable to set an estimated value of power required to maintain a predetermined process temperature. The system automatically adjusts the power supplied to the tape to the estimated value by means of a feedback control system. A process temperature sensor also regulates the power supplied to the tape in accordance with a sensed temperature.

column13: 678,772. Automatic regulation; rectifying. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. April 10, 1951 [July 12, 1950], No. 17500/50. Classes 38 (ii) and 38 (iv). Where two or more D.C. power supply units are fed through a common impedance from a source, a second common impedance is included in a common D.C. return path for the units to compensate, to a desired degree, for voltage variations due to the first common impedance. Rectifiers R1, R2 supplied from a common A.C. source M, supply loads RFD, HRF respectively. Variations in the voltage supplied to load RFD, due to variations of load HRF causing changes in volt-drop across a common impedance X, are compensated by introducing the volt-drop across a resistance Y in series with the supply to load RFD. By choice of resistance Y the voltage supply to load RFD which may be the H.T. load of the driver stage of a television transmitter is thus exactly over-, or under-compensated for variations of load HRF which may be the H.T. load of a modulated power amplifier stage of the transmitter. Common impedance X may be due to a voltage regulator associated with the A.C. source and resistance Y may be the lowest frequency section of a rectifier constant impedance filter network. A polyphase supply and more than two D.C. supplies are referred to.

The polysilicon layer is patterned to form the gate conductor, and a drain contact is formed on a bottom surface of the semiconductor substrate.

column13: A rotatable building structure that comprises: a vertically extending building having one or more floors; a fixed core support for supporting the building, located substantially centrally beneath the building; a rotatable annular drive system for rotating the building, located lower than the building and with its centre substantially aligned with the vertical centreline of the building, the system having an upper surface and a planar lower surface; and a fixed outer support, located beneath the annular drive system, the support having a planar upper surface that contacts the planar lower surface of the annular drive system; wherein at least one of the lower surface of the annular drive system and the upper surface of the fixed outer support is a bearing material, permitting rotation of the annular drive system over the fixed outer support, such that the annular drive system is rotated via a planar to planar bearing system.

column12: Hydroformylation process employing tetracarboxylatodiruthenium halide complex catalyst
column13: Disclosed is a process for the hydroformylation of olefins (includes mixtures of olefins) of 2 to 20 carbons, and preferably of 3 to 10 carbons for the production of relatively high proportions of branched to linear aldehydes, and with especially good selectivity to the production of butyraldehydes from propylene, wherein the olefin is contacted in a reaction zone at a temperature of from about 70.degree. C. to about 250.degree. C., preferably from about 150.degree. C. to about 220.degree. C., and a pressure of from about 500 psig to about 10,000 psig, preferably from about 2,500 psig to about 3,500 psig with hydrogen and carbon monoxide in the presence of a catalytic amount of one or more tetracarboxylatodiruthenium halide complexes, i.e., an amount containing from about 10.sup.-7 to about 10.sup.-1, preferably from about 10.sup.-5 to about 10.sup.-3 moles of ruthenium per mole of olefin, for a sufficient period of time to permit reaction of the olefin with the hydrogen and carbon monoxide to form aldehyde product.

column12: Watermarked polymeric sheet and method of making the same
column13: A method of making a watermarked polymeric sheet includes forming a web ( 22 ) of a polymeric material, selectively irradiating portions of the web ( 22 ) with electromagnetic radiation, and stretching the web to form a sheet ( 26 ) having increased length and/or width. The watermarked polymeric sheet ( 26 ) has a plurality of indentations in at least one surface thereof, in areas corresponding to the irradiated portions of the web. The indentations form a watermark comprising areas of increased translucency, which is visible by transmitted light.

column12: Multicombination vehicle and method for transporting a payload in an underground mine
column13: A multicombination vehicle and method are provided for transporting a payload, such as a mined metal ore, over the roadways existing in an underground mine. The multicombination vehicle includes a powered towing unit, which may comprise a rigid body truck, and at least one towed unit mechanically coupled to the rigid body truck. The vehicle may also include a plurality of the towed units, with a forward most one of the units coupled to the rigid body truck and each adjacent pair of the towed units being coupled to one another. Each of the units includes a chassis, a plurality of wheeled axles connected to the chassis for supporting the respective unit as the vehicle travels over the roadways of the mine, and a draw frame attached to and extending rearwardly from the corresponding chassis, with a coupling attached to a rear end of the draw frame. Each towed unit may comprise a semi-trailer mounted on a dolly, with a drawbar attached to and extending forwardly from the dolly and connected with the coupling of the immediately forward unit of the vehicle. The multicombination vehicle is configured so as to minimize the swept path width of the vehicle as the vehicle negotiates turns. This is accomplished by providing each of the towed units with a dolly drawbar length having a value of less than 3.0 meters and establishing a ratio of the coupling overhang-to-wheelbase, for each of the units, of at least 0.5.

column12: Electronic logic to enhance switch reliability in detecting openings and closures of redundant switches
column13: A logic circuit is used to enhance redundant switch reliability. Two or more switches are monitored for logical high or low output. The output for the logic circuit produces a redundant and failsafe representation of the switch outputs. When both switch outputs are high, the output is high. Similarly, when both switch outputs are low, the logic circuit's output is low. When the output states of the two switches do not agree, the circuit resolves the conflict by memorizing the last output state which both switches were simultaneously in and produces the logical complement of this output state. Thus, the logic circuit of the present invention allows the redundant switches to be treated as if they were in parallel when the switches are open and as if they were in series when the switches are closed. A failsafe system having maximum reliability is thereby produced.

column13: A hydroformylation process employing a rhodium-containing catalyst for the preparation of aldehydes, principally those having relatively high proportions of branched isomer. These aldehydes are prepared by hydroformylating an olefin in liquid solvent with a mixture of hydrogen and carbon monoxide in the presence of the catalyst to form a liquid composition. At least a portion of this liquid composition is contacted with an oxygen containing gas prior to recovery of gaseous aldehyde by distillation and then it is distilled at a temperature of 120 or less. The liquid composition obtained from the distillation can be recycled to the hydroformylation reaction.

column12: HEAT TRACING TAPE AND POWER CONTROL SYSTEM
column13: A heat tracing tape which can be cut to required lengths has a heating element comprising at least two lengths of woven or braided resistance wire each in the form of a flat strip. The strips are encased in extruded silicone rubber whereby they are spaced from one another. The strips are electrically connected at one end by a connector and the tape is provided with a power supply termination either at its other end, or at a T-branch connection, for connecting the tape to the power control system. The power control system is adjustable to set an estimated value of power required to maintain a predetermined process temperature. The system automatically adjusts the power supplied to the tape to the estimated value by means of a feedback control system. A process temperature sensor also regulates the power supplied to the tape in accordance with a sensed temperature.

column12: Improvements in or relating to television transmission systems
column13: 794,531. Television. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO., Ltd. July 5, 1956 [Oct. 24, 1955], No. 30320/55. Class 40 (3). In a television system the rate of transmission of brightness information is made substantially constant, irrespective of picture content, thus effecting a better utilization of available transmission bandwith. This is achieved by deriving from picture signals generated by conventional constant velocity scanning a further picture signal of the velocity modulated scan type in which the velocity of scanning is determined by changes in slope of the original picture waveform (i.e. by variations in the brightness content). As shown in Figs. 1 and 2, picture signals (a) derived by scanning a scene A with a conventional constant velocity scanning camera B are supplied to a picture tube J and there reproduced as a picture, also with constant velocity scanning, after a predetermined time interval determined by a delay device H in the picture signal circuit and a delay device H<SP>1</SP> in the scanning circuit. The reproduced picture is then rescanned by a camera tube K the scanning circuit L of which varies the velocity of scan in accordance with control signals supplied thereto. The control signals are produced in a quantizing circuit G which, in response to input signals (e) derived in a circuit F which differentiates a sawtooth wave (d) generated in E under the control of the twice differentiated (in C and D producing waveforms (b) and (c) respectively) signal (a) from camera B, supplies the waveform (f) consisting of a series of pulses which can occupy only N discrete amplitude levels (N being equal to 3 in the arrangement shown) each level being inversely proportional to the frequency content of the original signal and each pulse occurring after a fixed time after changes in slope in the original signal (a). The signal output of tube K when the velocity of scanning is controlled in accordance with the pulse train (f) is shown in curve (h) whence it can be seen by comparison with curve (g), which is identical with curve (a) delayed, that a better utilization of bandwidth results. To enable the signals from tube K to be reproduced at a co-operating receiver the scanning control signals (f) are also displayed on a picture tube M and scanned by a camera tube O operating with the same velocity modulated scan as tube K thus producing scanning control signals (j) which after modulation on to a sub-carrier in P are then employed together with the output of tube K to modulate a main carrier for transmissions from transmitter Q. At a co-operating receiver the picture signals (h) and scanning control signals (j) are separately derived in a conventional circuit S, the former signals being employed to modulate the intensity of the beam in reproducing tube U and the latter signals to control the velocity of the scanning waveform generated by unit V in accordance with their amplitude. Specifications 399,469, 413,401, 427,625 and 427,630, [all in Group XL], are referred to.
